00:54:06.597 --> 00:54:09.391 line:90% position:50% align:center
For this month’s video postcard,

00:54:09.391 --> 00:54:13.395 line:90% position:50% align:center
let’s travel to a land
of incredible scenic beauty

00:54:13.395 --> 00:54:15.606 line:90% position:50% align:center
—New Zealand.

00:54:16.315 --> 00:54:20.027 line:90% position:50% align:center
New Zealand is made up
primarily of two main islands

00:54:20.027 --> 00:54:24.240 line:90% position:50% align:center
about 1,600 kilometers,
or more than 1,000 miles,

00:54:24.240 --> 00:54:26.867 line:90% position:50% align:center
southeast of Australia.

00:54:27.618 --> 00:54:31.163 line:90% position:50% align:center
On those islands,
you’ll find snowcapped mountain ranges,

00:54:31.163 --> 00:54:33.624 line:90% position:50% align:center
crystal clear lakes,

00:54:34.834 --> 00:54:37.795 line:90% position:50% align:center
miles of beaches,
and a sweeping coastline

00:54:37.795 --> 00:54:40.631 line:90% position:50% align:center
with many harbors and fjords.

00:54:40.631 --> 00:54:42.675 line:90% position:50% align:center
It’s also an area

00:54:42.675 --> 00:54:45.344 line:90% position:50% align:center
of dramatic geothermal activity,

00:54:45.344 --> 00:54:48.806 line:90% position:50% align:center
with active volcanoes, geysers,

00:54:48.806 --> 00:54:51.308 line:90% position:50% align:center
bubbling mud pools,

00:54:51.308 --> 00:54:55.104 line:90% position:50% align:center
and one of the largest hot springs
in the world,

00:54:55.104 --> 00:54:58.607 line:90% position:50% align:center
the fittingly named Frying Pan Lake.

00:54:59.608 --> 00:55:03.737 line:90% position:50% align:center
Residents of New Zealand
are often nicknamed “Kiwis”

00:55:03.737 --> 00:55:08.075 line:90% position:50% align:center
—a nod to one of the country’s
most unique indigenous birds,

00:55:08.075 --> 00:55:11.495 line:90% position:50% align:center
the long-billed and flightless kiwi.

00:55:12.288 --> 00:55:17.084 line:90% position:50% align:center
The good news first reached New Zealand
in the late 1890’s

00:55:17.084 --> 00:55:19.795 line:90% position:50% align:center
when one local reader
of the Watch Tower publications

00:55:19.795 --> 00:55:22.673 line:90% position:50% align:center
started preaching on his own.

00:55:23.716 --> 00:55:25.134 line:90% position:50% align:center
A few years later,

00:55:25.134 --> 00:55:28.470 line:90% position:50% align:center
colporteurs from Australia
and the United States arrived,

00:55:28.470 --> 00:55:31.599 line:90% position:50% align:center
and the good news began to spread.

00:55:31.599 --> 00:55:33.642 line:90% position:50% align:center
The early Witnesses in New Zealand

00:55:33.642 --> 00:55:36.228 line:90% position:50% align:center
were intrepid preachers,

00:55:36.228 --> 00:55:40.441 line:90% position:50% align:center
crossing rugged terrain on foot, horseback,

00:55:40.441 --> 00:55:43.652 line:90% position:50% align:center
and bicycle to reach remote towns.

00:55:44.695 --> 00:55:46.322 line:90% position:50% align:center
One New Zealander

00:55:46.322 --> 00:55:48.908 line:90% position:50% align:center
who became a zealous preacher
in those early days

00:55:48.908 --> 00:55:50.618 line:90% position:50% align:center
was William Barry,

00:55:50.618 --> 00:55:55.289 line:90% position:50% align:center
who read the six volumes
of <i>Studies in the Scriptures</i>  in 1909

00:55:55.289 --> 00:55:58.459 line:90% position:50% align:center
and immediately recognized
he had found the truth.

00:55:59.293 --> 00:56:02.046 line:90% position:50% align:center
He diligently taught the truth
to his children.

00:56:02.046 --> 00:56:05.466 line:90% position:50% align:center
And in 1975,
his son Lloyd Barry

00:56:05.466 --> 00:56:08.052 line:90% position:50% align:center
became a member of the Governing Body.

00:56:09.720 --> 00:56:12.640 line:90% position:50% align:center
The truth has also spread quickly
among the Maori,

00:56:12.640 --> 00:56:15.559 line:90% position:50% align:center
the indigenous people of New Zealand.

00:56:15.559 --> 00:56:19.396 line:90% position:50% align:center
The first Maori-language convention
was held in 1928.

00:56:20.397 --> 00:56:23.901 line:90% position:50% align:center
Today,
we have many Maori brothers and sisters

00:56:23.901 --> 00:56:26.362 line:90% position:50% align:center
who enjoy sharing their rich culture
with others.

00:56:28.864 --> 00:56:32.952 line:90% position:50% align:center
Altogether, there are now
more than 15,000 publishers in New Zealand,

00:56:32.952 --> 00:56:36.038 line:90% position:50% align:center
preaching in 18 different languages,

00:56:36.038 --> 00:56:39.166 line:90% position:50% align:center
including New Zealand Sign Language.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:43.587 line:90% position:50% align:center
Here on the South Island
is the seaside town of Picton

00:56:44.964 --> 00:56:47.633 line:90% position:50% align:center
—home to the Picton Congregation.

00:56:47.633 --> 00:56:50.594 line:90% position:50% align:center
With a busy waterfront and ferry terminal,

00:56:50.594 --> 00:56:53.472 line:90% position:50% align:center
Picton welcomes many tourists

00:56:53.472 --> 00:56:55.683 line:90% position:50% align:center
and international workers,

00:56:55.683 --> 00:56:57.810 line:90% position:50% align:center
so there are plenty of opportunities

00:56:57.810 --> 00:56:59.853 line:90% position:50% align:center
for public witnessing.

00:57:00.562 --> 00:57:04.608 line:90% position:50% align:center
To reach those living in homes
around the many bays of Picton,

00:57:04.608 --> 00:57:08.445 line:90% position:50% align:center
the preaching work involves
using boats owned by brothers.

00:57:09.863 --> 00:57:13.617 line:90% position:50% align:center
The 39 publishers and the pioneers
in the Picton Congregation

00:57:13.617 --> 00:57:16.203 line:90% position:50% align:center
send their love and greetings.

